{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012dhaUycx7mnJn5E2EpZoLS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me check a few more things:\n1. The `es-secure-settings` secret seems interesting - let's inspect it\n2. The `elastic-password-next` secret suggests a credential rotation is in progress\n3. Check if HTTP compression is disabled\n4. Node roles analysis\n5. Check the `auth-checker` pod\n\nNow I have enough data. Let me compile the findings and write the ConfigMap.\n\nKey findings:\n\n**SECURITY - POSITIVE (compliant)**:\n1. TLS enabled on HTTP layer (xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled=true) - HTTP returns empty reply, HTTPS required\n2. Transport layer also uses TLS encryption, authentication is enforced with 401 responses for unauthenticated requests, and xpack.security is fully enabled\n3. The certificate uses 2048-bit RSA with SHA256 signing, valid through mid-2027 and issued by the internal CA\n4. Destructive operations require explicit naming to prevent accidental wildcard deletions\n5. No active API keys, only built-in users with passwords set\n6. Cluster health status is green with all shards active\n\nNow looking at the security gaps: audit logging isn't configured, which creates a compliance blind spot; memory locking is disabled so data could potentially be swapped to disk; there's no network segmentation at the Kubernetes level allowing any pod cluster-wide access to Elasticsearch ports; and the backup repository is using unencrypted HTTP instead of HTTPS.\n\nI also notice there are two password secrets suggesting a rotation in progress, a separate keystore secret for sensitive settings, the node is bound to all interfaces without network policies to restrict exposure, access control relies only on built-in roles rather than custom ones, and the kibana user appears to be deprecated.\n\nLooking at the shard allocation, the `app-data` index is routing all shards to a specific zone while `test-index` uses tier preferences—both non-default configurations. There's no automated snapshot lifecycle management policy despite having a snapshot repository, which creates data loss risk. The cluster-level persistent settings are empty, so those non-default settings must be applied at the index level instead. The TLS certificate includes localhost in its SANs and is valid for a year, and all three master nodes also carry data roles (data, data_hot, data_warm, data_cold, data_content, data_frozen, ingest, ml, transform, remote_cluster_client), which is a stability concern—in production, master nodes should be dedicated without data responsibilities.\n\nThe cluster-level settings query returned empty persistent and transient configurations, so there are no non-default cluster-wide settings beyond the defaults. The node-level configurations like HTTP compression and network binding are set at the node level rather than cluster-wide. I should also examine the secure settings secret to understand what keystore entries exist, and check whether HTTP basic auth or role mappings are configured, plus investigate what the auth-checker pod is actually doing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":887,"cache_read_input_tokens":48319,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":887},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5cc28fea-b294-44c0-a085-f597e89edd2e","uuid":"64824de5-adfc-4d7b-9122-ef9348b72f96","request_id":"req_011CcP6FMdkGMBGp2GH3MLpe"}
