{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JpnWPUnGZbApzgcoJbpX91","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RWC8JGNSu9HuyenRB2ZeyB","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n elasticsearch create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS'\n=============================================================\nELASTICSEARCH SECURITY & COMPLIANCE AUDIT FINDINGS\nCluster: es-cluster  |  Namespace: elasticsearch\nDate: 2026-06-24  |  Auditor: automated read-only audit\n=============================================================\n\nCLUSTER OVERVIEW\n----------------\n- Elasticsearch version: 8.11.1\n- Nodes: 5 total (3 master+data: es-0/1/2, 2 dedicated data: es-data-0/1)\n- StatefulSets: es (3/3), es-data (2/2)\n- Cluster health: GREEN (6 shards active, 0 unassigned)\n- Indices: test-index (1p/1r), app-data (1p/1r)\n\n=============================================================\n1. TLS / ENCRYPTION IN TRANSIT\n=============================================================\n\n[PASS] HTTP TLS enforced: xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled=true on all nodes.\n       Plain HTTP (port 9200) returns an empty reply; clients must use HTTPS.\n\n[PASS] Transport TLS enforced: xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled=true on all\n       5 nodes. Intra-cluster node-to-node traffic is encrypted.\n\n[PASS] TLS certificate: RSA-2048, SHA-256, CA=CN=es-ca, Subject=CN=es-http.\n       Validity: 2026-06-25 to 2027-06-25 (~1 year).\n       SANs: localhost, *.elasticsearch.svc, *.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local,\n             es-http, es-http.elasticsearch.svc, es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n\n[WARN] Self-signed internal CA (CN=es-ca). Acceptable for cluster-internal use\n       but must be explicitly trusted by all clients; not browser/OS trusted.\n\n[WARN] SAN includes DNS:localhost. While not externally exploitable in this\n       topology, it broadens the certificate's valid identity surface.\n\n[FAIL] Snapshot repository (minio-repo, type=s3) uses protocol=http — backup\n       traffic to MinIO at minio.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local:9000 is\n       transmitted in plaintext. S3 credentials and backup data are exposed\n       to any node on the pod network during snapshot operations.\n       Setting:  \"protocol\": \"http\"  (should be \"https\")\n\n=============================================================\n2. AUTHENTICATION\n=============================================================\n\n[PASS] xpack.security.enabled=true on all nodes.\n\n[PASS] Authentication required on all REST endpoints. Unauthenticated requests\n       return HTTP 401 with WWW-Authenticate: Basic/Bearer/ApiKey.\n\n[PASS] Anonymous access is disabled (no anonymous role mapping, no anonymous\n       user configuration found).\n\n[PASS] No active API keys.\n\n[FAIL] Credential rotation side-effect: two password secrets coexist.\n       Secret 'elastic-password' and 'elastic-password-next' are both present.\n       The active password matches the value in 'elastic-password-next', which\n       means 'elastic-password' is stale. The 'auth-checker' Deployment reads\n       from 'elastic-password' (the old secret) and its readiness probe is\n       currently FAILING. Stale credential secrets must be cleaned up after\n       rotation to avoid confusion and probe failures.\n\n=============================================================\n3. USER ACCOUNTS & ROLES\n=============================================================\n\n[PASS] No custom user accounts. Only built-in reserved users exist:\n       elastic (superuser), kibana_system (kibana_system role),\n       logstash_system, beats_system, apm_system, remote_monitoring_user.\n\n[PASS] No custom roles or role mappings configured.\n\n[WARN] Deprecated 'kibana' user is still present and enabled\n       (metadata._deprecated=true, superseded by 'kibana_system').\n       If this user is not in active use it should be disabled to reduce\n       the attack surface.\n\n[WARN] No least-privilege service accounts. All operational access routes\n       through the 'elastic' superuser. No application-specific users with\n       scoped index privileges exist. This violates least-privilege principles:\n       a compromised client credential yields full cluster access.\n\n[WARN] No role mappings configured. All authentication relies on username/\n       password via the native realm. LDAP/SSO integration is not configured.\n\n=============================================================\n4. AUDIT LOGGING\n=============================================================\n\n[FAIL] Security audit logging is NOT enabled on any node.\n       xpack.security.audit.enabled is absent from all node settings.\n       Without audit logging, there is no record of:\n         - Authentication successes and failures\n         - Authorization decisions\n         - Privileged operations (index create/delete, user management)\n         - Data access patterns\n       This is a gap against SOC 2, PCI-DSS, HIPAA, and most compliance\n       frameworks that mandate audit trails for data-at-rest stores.\n       Remediation: set xpack.security.audit.enabled=true and configure\n       xpack.security.audit.logfile.events.include appropriately.\n\n=============================================================\n5. NETWORK EXPOSURE & NETWORK POLICIES\n=============================================================\n\n[FAIL] No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy resources exist in the elasticsearch\n       namespace. Any pod in any namespace can connect to es-http:9200 and\n       all node transport ports 9300. Authentication is the only control\n       preventing unauthorized access to data.\n       Remediation: deploy NetworkPolicy to restrict ingress on 9200/9300\n       to known consumer namespaces/pods only.\n\n[WARN] All nodes bind network.host=0.0.0.0. Standard for Kubernetes but\n       combined with the absence of NetworkPolicies means the entire pod\n       network has unrestricted connectivity to the cluster.\n\n[INFO] es-http service is ClusterIP (not NodePort/LoadBalancer). Elasticsearch\n       is not directly exposed outside the cluster at the service level.\n\n=============================================================\n6. INDEX SETTINGS & DATA SECURITY\n=============================================================\n\nIndex: test-index\n  - Shards: 1 primary, 1 replica\n  - Routing: allocation.include._tier_preference=data_content (default tier)\n  - Security: no field-level or document-level security configured\n\nIndex: app-data\n  - Shards: 1 primary, 1 replica\n  - Routing: allocation.require.zone=new (pinned to es-data-0/1 nodes)\n  [WARN] Non-default shard routing — app-data shards are constrained to the\n         'new' zone. If es-data-0 and es-data-1 both fail, shards become\n         unassigned. No fallback zone is configured.\n  - Security: no field-level or document-level security configured\n\n[WARN] action.auto_create_index=true (cluster default). An authenticated client\n       writing to a previously unknown index name will automatically create\n       that index. Without index name restrictions, this may lead to\n       uncontrolled index proliferation.\n\n[PASS] action.destructive_requires_name=true. Wildcard-based destructive\n       operations (e.g. DELETE _all) are blocked.\n\n[WARN] No index-level access control (document-level security or field-level\n       security) is configured on either index. Any authenticated user with\n       index read privilege can access all fields and all documents.\n\n=============================================================\n7. CLUSTER SETTINGS (PERSISTENT/TRANSIENT)\n=============================================================\n\n[INFO] Cluster-level persistent and transient settings: both are empty {}.\n       All effective settings derive from static node configuration (elasticsearch.yml).\n\n[WARN] bootstrap.memory_lock=false (cluster default). Elasticsearch heap memory\n       is not locked and can be paged to disk swap. Sensitive data (index\n       buffers, credentials in memory) could be written to swap and persist\n       on disk unencrypted after a crash. Remediation: set\n       bootstrap.memory_lock=true and ensure ulimit -l unlimited.\n\n[WARN] http.compression=false on all nodes. HTTP response bodies are not\n       compressed. This is not a security risk but significantly increases\n       bandwidth consumption for large query responses. Standard hardening\n       guides recommend enabling compression.\n\n=============================================================\n8. SNAPSHOT & BACKUP\n=============================================================\n\n[WARN] Snapshot repository 'minio-repo' is configured (type=s3, bucket=es-backups,\n       endpoint=minio.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local:9000).\n\n[FAIL] No Snapshot Lifecycle Management (SLM) policy is configured.\n       The repository exists but no automated snapshot schedule is in place.\n       Data recovery is not guaranteed without regular automated snapshots.\n\n[FAIL] Backup transport is unencrypted (protocol=http). See TLS section above.\n\n[INFO] S3 credentials (access_key, secret_key) are stored in the\n       'es-secure-settings' Kubernetes Secret as ES keystore entries.\n       This is the correct approach; credentials are not hardcoded in\n       the snapshot repository configuration.\n\n=============================================================\n9. NODE ROLES & OPERATIONAL RISK\n=============================================================\n\n[WARN] Master-eligible nodes (es-0, es-1, es-2) also hold data, ingest, ml,\n       and transform roles. In production deployments, master nodes should be\n       dedicated (no data/ingest roles) to prevent GC pauses or I/O pressure\n       on data roles from destabilizing master elections and cluster state.\n       Dedicated data nodes (es-data-0, es-data-1) exist but only serve 2 of 5\n       nodes in the data tier.\n\n[PASS] 3 master-eligible nodes provide quorum (minimum_master_nodes=2).\n       cluster.election.strategy=supports_voting_only is configured.\n\n[INFO] No Certificate Revocation List (CRL) or OCSP configuration found.\n       Revoked certificates cannot be rejected dynamically.\n\n=============================================================\nSUMMARY TABLE\n=============================================================\n\nCategory                  | Status | Finding\n--------------------------|--------|----------------------------------\nHTTP TLS                  | PASS   | HTTPS enforced\nTransport TLS             | PASS   | Encrypted\nAuthentication            | PASS   | Required, no anonymous access\nAudit Logging             | FAIL   | Not enabled - compliance gap\nNetwork Policies          | FAIL   | None configured\nBackup TLS                | FAIL   | Snapshot repo uses plain HTTP\nSLM Snapshot Policy       | FAIL   | None configured\nCredential Rotation       | FAIL   | Stale secret, probe failing\nMemory Lock               | WARN   | bootstrap.memory_lock=false\nDeprecated Users          | WARN   | 'kibana' user still enabled\nLeast Privilege           | WARN   | Only superuser in practical use\nNode Role Separation      | WARN   | Masters double as data nodes\nAuto-create Index         | WARN   | Enabled, no restriction list\nShard Routing (app-data)  | WARN   | Single-zone pinning, no fallback\n\nTOTAL: 4 FAIL  |  8 WARN  |  Multiple PASS\n\nRemediation priority: (1) enable audit logging, (2) deploy NetworkPolicies,\n(3) encrypt snapshot traffic, (4) configure SLM policy, (5) clean up stale\ncredential secret, (6) disable deprecated kibana user, (7) create least-\nprivilege application users.\nFINDINGS\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1129,"cache_read_input_tokens":51078,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1129},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5cc28fea-b294-44c0-a085-f597e89edd2e","uuid":"3a20bf47-8395-46f1-84d8-25204a182f1b","request_id":"req_011CcP6Jihr1BDtvcS2ABYe8"}
